## AI Review Standards

### Code Review Discipline
- NEVER rubber-stamp Claude Code or any AI output — review every diff critically
- Summarizing what changed is NOT the same as validating it is correct
- Always check: does this match the original design intent? Are interfaces preserved?
- Flag logic errors, missing guards, threshold issues BEFORE accepting edits

### Testing Strategy
- Always test on the HARDEST case first, not the easiest
- Sample validation before full runs — 20 pages before 500 pages, 1 source before all
- If a full run takes >10 minutes, find a faster validation path first
- Never commit to expensive compute without a cheap sanity check first

### Auto-suggestion Discipline
- Claude Code auto-suggestions are NOT instructions — evaluate before accepting
- If auto-suggestion skips a validation step, override it
- "Proceed" and "looks good" require explicit reasoning, not just pattern matching

### Debugging Approach
- Test on most complex/edge case to build real confidence
- Isolate and validate components before running full pipeline
- When something looks wrong, re-analyze root cause before applying fixes
- Don't fix symptoms — find and fix the actual cause

### Threshold and Logic Review
- Every threshold needs a word_count or scope guard to prevent noise triggering
- Check logic ORDER — conditions evaluated top to bottom, order matters
- Low thresholds (< 0.20, < 2) need explicit justification
- When in doubt, start conservative (higher threshold) and tune down

### General Principles
- Push back when AI moves too fast
- Re-analyze before saying continue
- Prioritize correctness over speed
- Human checkpoint between AI-generated code and production runs

## Multi-Agent Review Process

Before writing ANY new file or component:
1. Load .claude/architect.md — review structure
2. Load .claude/business.md — review user value
3. Load .claude/critic.md — challenge assumptions
4. Load .claude/qa.md — validate test coverage
5. Reconcile all four before writing code

Mandatory for: new files, schema changes, threshold values, pipeline changes, API integrations
